The Sustainability pillar.

Sustainability is the newest pillar, added in twenty twenty-one, and it's about minimising the environmental impact of running cloud workloads. The lens is: less compute consumed, fewer resources idle, and more efficient hardware.

Most of the checklist overlaps with Cost Optimization, because efficiency saves both money and carbon. Right-size and decommission idle resources, since the same lever that saves money saves carbon. Use modern instance generations, because Graviton processors consume meaningfully less power per unit of work than older x-eighty-six. Prefer serverless and managed services, which share underlying hardware, raise utilisation, and cut the per-customer footprint. Use storage tiering, since Glacier Deep Archive uses dramatically less energy than Standard for the same bytes at scale. Choose your Region: A-W-S publishes carbon intensity per Region, and some run on significantly more renewable energy, so for latency-flexible workloads a greener Region is a free win. And right-size the whole demand curve, with smaller data formats, efficient code, batching, and lifecycle deletion all reducing the work done.

The design principles: understand your impact, set goals, maximise utilisation, anticipate and adopt more efficient hardware, use managed services, and reduce the downstream impact of your workloads. The one-line takeaway is that the greenest and the cheapest architectures are usually the same architecture. Sustainability rarely asks for a different design than cost; it just asks you to count carbon alongside dollars. The cue, minimise environmental impact or reduce carbon footprint, points to this pillar, answered mostly with right-sizing, Graviton, serverless, and tiering.
